## we can use a tree traversal to compute all paths and print all of them out 
class path:
    def __init__(self):
        self.size = 0 
        self.pathway = [0b000]## we start with 000

    def clone(self):
        P = path()
        P.size =self.size
        P.pathway = self.pathway.copy()
        return P
    
    def last(self):
        return self.pathway[self.size]
    
    def append(self,vec):
        self.size += 1
        self.pathway.append(vec)

    def __str__(self):
        binary_path = [bin(x)[2:].zfill(3) for x in self.pathway]  # Convert to binary
        return str(binary_path)  # Return the binary representation
    
    def isValidMove(self, move):
        return not(move in self.pathway)
        

def find(path):
    global count  

    if path.last() == 7:  
        count += 1
        print(f"Path {count}: {path}") # Print the complete path only when it reaches 7
        return # stop further exploration once we reach 7
    else:
        for move_bit in [0b001, 0b010, 0b100]: # Iterate over the move bits
            new_move = path.last() ^ move_bit
            if path.isValidMove(new_move):
                P = path.clone()
                P.append(new_move)
                find(P)

count =0
def main():
    print("start___finding pathways")
    P = path()
    find(P)

if __name__=="__main__":
    main()

so we know by doing a tree traversal of the graph we have 18 paths but we should thing of this in a more mathematical way 

if we start at node 1 [0,0,0] we have 3 options
so our possibility become 3 * P where P is the rest of the expression

then at the second depth we have 2 valid moves so 
3 * 2 * P 

then we are at something like [1,1,0]
we still have 2 options for any of the nodes in this layer so
3 * 2 * 2 * P 

this is where it gets tricky
2 of the nodes at this depth lead back to have 2 options [1,0,0] and [0,0,1] but the other only have 1 option 
so we would only half to add the remaining paths to the current number witch is 4 

we then get 3 * 2 * 2 + 4 = 16
